Bring a large #pot{} of @salted water{} to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @shallot{1}. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}.

Pat @chicken cutlets{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; place between two large pieces of #plastic wrap{}. Pound with a #mallet{} or #rolling pin{} until chicken is about ½ inch thick. Season all over with @Italian seasoning{1/4%tsp}, @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> Be sure to measure the Italian Seasoning—we sent more!

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add chicken and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes} per side. Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{} and tent with #foil{} to keep warm. Wipe out pan.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for chicken over medium-high heat. Add shallot and cook, stirring, until softened and lightly browned, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in @spinach{5%ounce} and garlic; cook, stirring occasionally, until spinach begins to wilt and garlic is fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes} more.

Once water is boiling, add @butternut squash agnolotti{9%ounce} to pot; cook until al dente and floating to the top, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Reserve 1 1/2 cups pasta cooking water, then drain.

To pan with veggies, add @cheese roux concentrate{1%ounce} and 1 cup reserved pasta cooking water; stir to combine. Cook, stirring, until slightly thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Reduce heat to medium low, then stir in @cream cheese{2%tbsp} and half the @Parmesan cheese{3%tbsp}. Taste and season with salt and pepper. Turn off heat.

Cut chicken into bite-size pieces.

Stir drained agnolotti, half the chicken, and @butter{1%tbsp} into pan with sauce and toss until coated.

> If sauce seems too thick, stir in more reserved pasta cooking water a splash at a time.

Divide pasta between plates; top with remaining chicken and remaining Parmesan. Serve.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.